Q1 (A) – Short Answers

a) Why configure enable password?
Protects privileged EXEC mode (Router#)
Prevents unauthorized configuration changes
Without it → anyone can access full control

b) Role of VLAN1 in initial configuration
Default VLAN on switch
Used for management (IP address assignment)
All ports belong to VLAN1 initially

c) Static NAT Configuration (1-to-1 mapping)
Example:
Private IP: 192.168.1.2
Public IP: 200.1.1.1
enable
configure terminal
interface g0/0
ip address 192.168.1.1 255.255.255.0
ip nat inside
no shutdown
interface g0/1
ip address 200.1.1.2 255.255.255.0
ip nat outside
no shutdown
ip nat inside source static 192.168.1.2 200.1.1.1

d) Dynamic NAT with pool
access-list 1 permit 192.168.1.0 0.0.0.255
ip nat pool MYPOOL 200.1.1.1 200.1.1.10 netmask 255.255.255.0
ip nat inside source list 1 pool MYPOOL

f) Define Hashing
Converts data into fixed-size value (hash)
Used in:
Password storage
Data integrity
Example: SHA, MD5

g) Cyber Security Policies
Rules to protect systems and data
Examples:
Password policy
Access control policy
Data backup policy
Network security policy

✅ Q2 (B) –Ping Command


#include <stdio.h>
#include <stdlib.h> 
int main()
{
printf("--- Network Configuration Verification Program ---\n\n");
printf("Step 1: Fetching current running configuration...\n");
int config_status = system("show running-config");
if (config_status == -1)
{
printf("Error: Could not execute configuration command.\n");
}
else
{
printf("\nConfiguration fetch completed with status: %d\n",config_status);
} 
printf("\n--------------------------------------------------\n");
char target_ip[] = "8.8.8.8";
printf("Step 2: Pinging %s to verify connectivity...\n", target_ip);
char ping_cmd[50];
sprintf(ping_cmd, "ping -c 4 %s", target_ip);
int ping_status = system(ping_cmd);
if (ping_status == 0)
{
printf("\nResult: SUCCESS - Target %s is reachable.\n", target_ip);
} 
else 
{
printf("\nResult: FAILED - Target %s is unreachable.\n", target_ip);
}
return 0;
}





